    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/0zu4m.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 8463731,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6348498,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6348498/gurwinder-singh",
                "reputation": 39709,
                "display_name": "Gurwinder Singh",
                "accept_rate": 92
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1482647168,
            "creation_date": 1482640589,
            "body": "<p>If the Menu is not launching new threads, then there is nothing to talk of about. But, if the <code>Menu<\/code> does things in threads (something like):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>void doStuff() {\n    new Thread(()-&gt;{\n    //do work here\n    }).start();\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or may be in the constructor (Don't do this - causes reference escape causes thread unsafe operations) itself:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Menu() {\n  //create a thread here\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>the reference to this object is still in use by the newly spawned thread, even if you change the reference where you created a new instance:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Menu menu = new Menu();//initialize --&gt; spawned a new thread here\n    menu.doStuff();  // --&gt; or here depending on where you did it\n    int x = menu.getNumbers;\n    menu = new Menu(); //reinitialize\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Reinitialising the variable <code>menu<\/code> will not kill the thread. The thread will run to its completion.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 41318711,
            "question_id": 41318663,
            "last_edit_date": 1482647168
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/89d5214e1671daad3cc34e1288b6a18d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 9446844,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 7025250,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7025250/steeltoe",
                "reputation": 2625,
                "display_name": "SteelToe",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1482640688,
            "creation_date": 1482640688,
            "body": "<p>As explained in this link <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2423284/java-thread-garbage-collected-or-not\">Java Thread Garbage collected or not<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>As long as a thread is live, meaning that it is still running code then the thread will continue to run even though though a reference to that thread object is lost. This is due to the nature of the garbage collector, that it will not destroy a live thread (Think why the main thread never gets destroyed even though there is no reference).<\/p>\n\n<p>This is why even if you lose a reference to an object that has a thread in it, like the object Menu in your case, the thread will still run until it finishes.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 41318719,
            "question_id": 41318663,
            "last_edit_date": 1495539960
        }
    ],
